  "doc_id": "22142",
  "text": "For Sinclair et al. (2005, 70) , the failure to integrate MFA into policy persists because \". . . no integrated model has been proposed that is capable of either mapping or predicting regional flows on a disaggregated basis. Nor does one exist that links these flows to regional and national economic accounting data.\" As such research on MFA and urban metabolism has not tended to inform planning policy and practice, apart from a number of key exceptions noted by [CITATION_1] , including attempts at developing sustainability indicators and major urban reconstruction. This situation means the two disciplines have progressed largely independently and leaving opportunities for cross-fertilisation rather neglected.",
